    <li>
      <p>Many cornfield flowers have disappeared from the countryside and are
        amongst the rarest plants in Britain.</p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>Their history is entwined with that of farming so they have a special
        place in our culture.</p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>A diversity of flowers at the edge of fields provide nectar and pollen
        vital for bees, and food for other beneficial insects and birds.</p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>They form the base of the food chain for a healthy farmland ecosystem.</p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>Conservation of cornfield flowers is compatible with modern, commercial
        agriculture.</p>
    </li>
